s are chosen at random and may be observed by marketing professionals.\n2,MARKET RESEARCH,Market Research involves the systematic gathering and analyzing of data about consumers, competitors, and market conditions to inform business decisions. It provides insights into market trends, customer preferences, and competitive dynamics. This process can be based on primary or secondary data and is used to assess the potential success of new product launches. By understanding consumers' needs and preferences, companies can make informed decisions about product development and marketing strategies. Market Research serves as an external source of valuable information that helps businesses navigate the competitive landscape effectively.\n3. SENSITIVITY ANALYSIS, Sensitivity analysis calculates how responsive a decision is to changes in any of the variables used to calculate it.\nRelationships\n\nid,source,target,description\n10,FOCUS GROUP,MARKET RESEARCH,Focus group is related to market research. They are both research techniques to deal with uncertainty.\n11,MARKET RESEARCH,FOCUS GROUP,Market research is related to focus group. They are both research techniques to deal with uncertainty.\n\nOutput:\n{{\n    \"title\": \"Chapter 8: Risk and Uncertainty\",\n    \"summary\": \"Chapter 8 covers the following Learning Outcomes. C. Decision-Making Techniques 6. Dealing with risk and uncertainty in decision making a) Suggest research techniques to reduce uncertainty (e.g. focus groups, market research). b) Explain the use of simulation, expected values and sensitivity. c) Apply expected values and sensitivity to decision-making problems. d) Apply the techniques of maximax, maximin and minimax regret to decision-making problems, including the production of profit tables. e) Interpret a decision tree and use it to solve a multi-stage decision problem. f) Calculate the value of perfect and imperfect information. \",\n    \"rating\": 7.0,\n    \"rating_explanation\": \"The impact severity rating is high due to the fundamental importance of bookkeeping in accounting.\",\n    \"findings\": [\n        {{\n            \"summary\": \"Focus groups and market research are important research techniques to reduce uncertainty\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Companies often use focus groups and/or market research to deal with uncertainty. Focus groups are used to reduce uncertainty about new products by gathering opinions from a group of people in an interactive environment. Participants are chosen at random and may be observed by marketing professionals. Market Research involves the systematic gathering and analyzing of data about consumers, competitors, and market conditions to inform business decisions. It provides insights into market trends, customer preferences, and competitive dynamics. This process can be based on primary or secondary data and is used to assess the potential success of new product launches. By understanding consumers' needs and preferences, companies can make informed decisions about product development and marketing strategies. Market Research serves as an external source of valuable information that helps businesses navigate the competitive landscape effectively. [Data: Concepts (1, 2); Relationships (10, 11)]\"\n        }},\n        {{\n            \"summary\": \"Explain and apply sensitivity analysis to decision-making problems\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Sensitivity analysis calculates how responsive a decision is to changes in any of the variables used in making that decision. It looks at one variable at a time and measures how much the variable can change by (in percentage terms) before affecting the decision. The smaller the percentage, the more sensitive the decision is to that variable. Sensitivity % = Profit/Variable  [Data: Concepts (3)]\"\n        }}\n    ]\n}}\n\n# Real Data\n\nUse the following text for your answer. Do not make anything up in your answer.\n\nText:\n-----Entities-----\nhuman_readable_id,title,description,degree\n180,\"\"\"THROUGHPUT ACCOUNTING\"\"\",\"Throughput Accounting is a management accounting approach that focuses on maximizing the throughput, which is the rate at which the system generates money through sales, while minimizing inventory and operating expenses. This methodology prioritizes products based on their return per hour of bottleneck resource, calculated as throughput per unit divided by the bottleneck hour required to produce one unit. By drawing management\u2019s attention to bottleneck processes, Throughput Accounting aims to maximize the throughput generated per hour by eliminating these bottlenecks and focuses on throughput contribution, which is sales revenue less material cost.\n\nThroughput Accounting involves discussing and applying the theory of constraints, calculating and interpreting a throughput accounting ratio (TPAR), and suggesting ways to improve this ratio. It is also applied to multi-product decision-making problems to enhance overall system efficiency. The technique emphasizes the importance of managing bottlenecks to maximize the throughput return per production hour, calculated as the selling price minus material cost divided by bottleneck hours per unit.\",12\n196,\"\"\"THROUGHPUT ACCOUNTING RATIO (TPAR)\"\"\",The Throughput Accounting Ratio (TPAR) is a metric used in throughput accounting to measure the efficiency of a production process. It is calculated as the Return per factory hour divided by the Cost per factory hour. The Return per factory hour is determined by dividing the Throughput per unit by the Hours of bottleneck resource used per unit. The Cost per factory hour is calculated by dividing the Other factory costs by the Bottleneck resource hours available.,5\n602,\"\"\"KEY FACTOR ANALYSIS\"\"\",\"\"\"Key Factor Analysis is a decision-making approach that prioritizes production based on the contribution per limiting factor, assuming a single objective of profit maximization and constant variable and fixed costs.\"\"\",4\n1425,\"\"\"PRODUCTION RANKING\"\"\",\"\"\"Production ranking is the process of ordering products based on their throughput return per machine hour to maximize profits.\"\"\",2\n288,\"\"\"THROUGHPUT PER UNIT\"\"\",\"\"\"Throughput per unit\"\" is calculated as the selling price of a product minus the total variable costs associated with producing one unit of the product. This includes subtracting the direct materials cost from the selling price to determine the throughput per unit.\",2\n240,\"\"\"BOTTLENECK RESOURCE\"\"\",\"A Bottleneck Resource is a resource that limits the overall output of a production process due to its limited capacity. It is the part of the production process that has the least capacity and, as a result, restricts the overall output of the system.\",1\n1343,\"\"\"DEMAND PER PERIOD\"\"\",\"\"\"Demand per period refers to the number of units of a product that are required or expected to be sold in a given time period.\"\"\",1\n1341,\"\"\"QUIZ: THROUGHPUT ACCOUNTING PRIORITY\"\"\",\"\"\"This quiz involves determining the priority of products based on their throughput contribution, given their selling price, variable costs, fixed overhead costs, and demand per period.\"\"\",1\n1340,\"\"\"QUIZ: THROUGHPUT CONTRIBUTION PER HOUR\"\"\",\"\"\"This quiz involves calculating the throughput contribution per hour for a product, given its selling price, material cost, labour cost, overhead costs, and time on the bottleneck resource.\"\"\",1\n610,\"\"\"RETURN PER HOUR OF BOTTLENECK RESOURCE\"\"\",\"\"\"Return per hour of bottleneck resource is calculated by dividing the throughput per unit by the bottleneck hours required to produce one unit.\"\"\",1\n1351,\"\"\"RETURN PER HOUR QUIZ\"\"\",\"\"\"This quiz tests the calculation of return per hour for a product using throughput accounting. It involves determining the return per hour based on selling price, material costs, conversion costs, and time on the bottleneck resource.\"\"\",1\n1353,\"\"\"THROUGHPUT ACCOUNTING RATIO QUIZ\"\"\",\"\"\"This quiz involves calculating the throughput accounting ratio (TPAR) for a product, considering the return per factory hour and factory costs per hour. It tests understanding of throughput accounting principles.\"\"\",1\n604,\"\"\"SHADOW PRICE\"\"\",\"\"\"Shadow Price\"\" refers to the additional contribution generated if one more unit of a scarce resource becomes available. It represents the maximum premium over the normal price that a company would be willing to pay for each additional unit. In the context of linear programming, the shadow price is the change in the optimal value of the objective function per unit increase in the right-hand side of a constraint. Essentially, it is the amount by which the objective function, such as contribution, will increase if an extra unit of a scarce resource is obtained at the standard price. For example, for the company Cut and Stitch, the shadow price for fabric is $10 per meter. The shadow price is a critical measure as it indicates the maximum amount a company should pay for one more unit of a scarce resource, such as timber, based on the contribution that the additional unit would generate.\",5\n287,\"\"\"COST PER FACTORY HOUR\"\"\",\"\"\"Cost per factory hour is calculated as Other factory costs divided by Bottleneck resource hours available.\"\"\",3\n1429,\"\"\"GRAPHICAL LINEAR PROGRAMMING\"\"\",,3\n248,\"\"\"RETURN PER FACTORY HOUR\"\"\",\"\"\"Return per Factory Hour\"\" is a metric used to determine the profitability of products based on the time they spend in the production process. It is calculated as the throughput per unit divided by the hours of bottleneck resource used per unit.\",2\n2134,\"\"\"SPECIALIST TIMBER\"\"\",\"\"\"Specialist timber is a type of timber that is limited in supply to 20,000 square meters per annum due to a problem with the supplier.\"\"\",2\n605,\"\"\"DECISIONS WITH A LIMITING FACTOR\"\"\",\"\"\"Decisions with a Limiting Factor involve determining which products to make in-house and which to outsource based on the savings per unit of scarce resource, prioritizing those with the greatest savings.\"\"\",2\n282,\"\"\"INTERPRETING TPAR\"\"\",\"\"\"TPAR is interpreted as follows: If TPAR > 1, the product is profitable as the throughput contribution exceeds the fixed costs. If TPAR = 1, the product breaks even. If TPAR < 1, the product is loss-making as the throughput contribution does not cover the fixed costs required to make it.\"\"\",1\n283,\"\"\"WAYS TO IMPROVE TPAR\"\"\",\"\"\"Ways to improve TPAR include eliminating bottlenecks or reducing the time spent on bottleneck resources, reducing other factory costs, increasing selling prices, or reducing material costs. However, increasing selling prices may not be feasible in a competitive environment, and reducing material costs may affect quality.\"\"\",1\n603,\"\"\"LIMITATIONS OF KEY FACTOR ANALYSIS\"\"\",\"\"\"Limitations of Key Factor Analysis include assumptions of a single objective of profit maximization, constant variable and fixed costs, dealing with only one scarce resource, and applicability only to short-term capacity constraints.\"\"\",1\n289,\"\"\"BOTTLENECK RESOURCE HOURS AVAILABLE\"\"\",\"\"\"Bottleneck resource hours available refers to the total hours available for the bottleneck process in a given period.\"\"\",1\n290,\"\"\"OTHER FACTORY COSTS\"\"\",\"\"\"Other factory costs include all fixed and variable costs associated with running the factory, excluding direct material costs.\"\"\",1\n1424,\"\"\"QUIZ ON GRAPHICAL LINEAR PROGRAMMING\"\"\",\"\"\"This quiz tests knowledge on graphical linear programming with the objective of maximizing profit, including concepts like resource constraints and shadow prices.\"\"\",1\n1714,\"\"\"OPTIMUM PRODUCTION PLAN\"\"\",\"The \"\"OPTIMUM PRODUCTION PLAN\"\" involves maximizing contribution while considering constraints such as labor and machine time. This plan is determined by calculating the contribution per unit and per square meter of timber for each product, ranking them, and then allocating the available timber to maximize profit while meeting minimum order requirements.\",2\n606,\"\"\"MAKE OR BUY QUIZ\"\"\",\"\"\"The Make or Buy Quiz involves determining which components to make in-house and which to buy externally based on the savings per unit of scarce resource, given a limited supply of Material B.\"\"\",1\n1713,\"\"\"LABOUR AND MACHINE TIME INTERSECTION\"\"\",\"\"\"Labour and machine time intersect at the optimum point if shown on a graph.\"\"\",1\n1426,\"\"\"QUIZ ON PRODUCTION RANKING\"\"\",\"\"\"This quiz involves ranking products based on their throughput return per machine hour to determine the most profitable production order.\"\"\",1\n\n\n-----Relationships-----\nhuman_readable_id,source,target,description,rank\n217,\"\"\"THROUGHPUT ACCOUNTING\"\"\",\"\"\"THEORY OF CONSTRAINTS\"\"\",\"\"\"Theory of constraints is applied in throughput accounting to improve production efficiency.\"\"\",19\n218,\"\"\"THROUGHPUT ACCOUNTING\"\"\",\"\"\"THROUGHPUT ACCOUNTING RATIO (TPAR)\"\"\",\"\"\"Throughput accounting ratio (TPAR) is used in throughput accounting to measure process efficiency.\"\"\",17\n219,\"\"\"THROUGHPUT ACCOUNTING\"\"\",\"\"\"KEY FACTOR ANALYSIS\"\"\",\"\"\"Throughput Accounting can be used with Key Factor Analysis to maximize throughput by prioritizing products based on their return per hour of bottleneck resource.\"\"\",16\n228,\"\"\"THROUGHPUT ACCOUNTING\"\"\",\"\"\"PRODUCTION RANKING\"\"\",\"\"\"Production Ranking is based on Throughput accounting principles.\"\"\",14\n221,\"\"\"THROUGHPUT ACCOUNTING\"\"\",\"\"\"THROUGHPUT PER UNIT\"\"\",\"\"\"Throughput per unit is used in Throughput Accounting to calculate the return per hour of bottleneck resource.\"\"\",14\n220,\"\"\"THROUGHPUT ACCOUNTING\"\"\",\"\"\"BOTTLENECK RESOURCE\"\"\",\"\"\"Throughput Accounting focuses on maximizing throughput by prioritizing products based on their return per 